Part I - How Trip Data Attributes and Features Affect Duration¶

by Rahaf Bakeer¶

Introduction¶

This data collection contains rider-specific information from a bike-sharing system serving the whole San Francisco Bay area. The dataset includes details on about 183,000 rides. Features include duration (measured in seconds) and other characteristics like gender, the user type (customer or subscriber), and date and time. The member's birth year, the names of the start and finish stations, the longitude and latitude of each station, and the unique IDs of each station provide further details.

Column Name Description
duration_sec Duration of the trip in seconds.
start_time Start time of the trip.
end_time End time of the trip.
start_station_id ID of the start station.
start_station_name Name of the start station.
start_station_latitude Latitude of the start station.
start_station_longitude Longitude of the start station.
end_station_id ID of the end station.
end_station_name Name of the end station.
end_station_latitude Latitude of the end station.
end_station_longitude Longitude of the end station.
bike_id ID of the bike.
user_type Type of user (Customer or Subscriber).
member_birth_year Birth year of the member.
member_gender Gender of the member.
bike_share_for_all_trip Indicates if the bike share program is for all trips.

#Define a function to convert the types of the attributes
def convert_data_type(df,column_To_convert):
    for key,type in column_To_convert.items():
        df[key] = df[key].astype(type)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 183,412 rows of data that describe bike trips and the data set contain 16 columns that are ['duration_sec', 'start_time', 'end_time', 'start_station_id', 'start_station_name', 'start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name', 'end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude', 'bike_id', 'user_type', 'member_birth_year', 'member_gender', 'bike_share_for_all_trip'] The types of the attributes are int, bool, float, object, dateTime and category

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The duration_sec attribute and the user_type attribute are the features that I'm aiming to study for this dataset

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The features that will help with the study are member_gender, member_birth_year, start_station (latitude,longitude) end_station (latitude,longitude)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

For the duration_sec attribute histogram plot There are some outliers on the far right side of the histogram, indicating unusually long trip durations. These could represent cases where users kept the bikes for extended periods, possibly due to some reason. The sharp drop-off after 1,500 seconds shows that such long trips are relatively rare, suggesting that most users utilize the bike-sharing service for shorter commutes or recreational rides.

The histogram for member_birth_year attribute, The most noticeable feature is the sharp spike around the early 1990s, where the number of users significantly increases compared to surrounding birth years. There don't appear to be clear outliers in the birth years themselves, but the tapering towards the extremes (especially users born before the 1960s) could be viewed as unusual when compared to the bulk of users being younger

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

This box plot shows the distribution of trip durations for different user types (Customer and Subscriber). The plot reveals that Customers tend to have a wider range of trip durations, with several outliers indicating longer trips. On the other hand, Subscribers generally have shorter trips, as indicated by the median and interquartile range. The presence of outliers for both groups suggests that some users might be taking exceptionally long trips.

This scatterplot shows the relationship between trip duration (in seconds) and the member's birth year for both user type (Customer and Subscriber). The x-axis represents the birth year of the members, ranging from the late 1800s to around 2000, while the y-axis shows the duration of trips. The plot shows that members for both user types born after 1940 have a higher concentration of trips with varying durations. As birth years approach 2000, the spread of trip durations increases, indicating a wider range of trip lengths among younger members. The data suggests that younger members are more likely to take longer trips, while older members tend to have shorter and more consistent trip durations. The presence of some outliers with extremely long durations, particularly among younger members, is also notable.

This suggests that, as subscribers grow older, they may maintain more consistent and somewhat longer trip durations, possibly due to habitual or routine use of the service, as opposed to customers who might engage in shorter, less frequent trips as they age

This scatterplot visualizes the relationship between trip duration (in seconds) and the birth year of users for a bike-sharing dataset. Multiple encodings are used to distinguish between different user types and bike IDs. The x-axis represents the member birth year, and the y-axis shows the trip duration. The color of the dots indicates the user type, with red for customers and blue for subscribers. Additionally, the size of the dots represents the bike ID, with larger dots corresponding to higher bike IDs.The plot shows that most of the data points are clustered between birth years 1950 and 2000. There some outliers for older birth years. Also the plot shows that subscribers are the predominant user type in the dataset.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Age and user type seem to strengthen each other when looking at trip duration. Younger customers tend to have longer trips, especially compared to subscribers, indicating that the type of user (whether they are subscribed or just one-time customers) has a significant impact on how long they tend to use the service. The distribution of trip durations by gender is fairly consistent, with slight variations. The key observation is that males and females mostly engage in shorter trips, but there is more variability in the "Other" gender category, indicating that gender identity may influence trip behavior in ways that are less predictable

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One of the more surprising interactions is the tendency for younger customer users (those born after 1980) to engage in much longer trips compared to subscribers. While it's expected that younger users might be more active, the extent of the difference in trip duration especially those exceeding 20,000 seconds is unexpected. This might suggest that customer users, who are not regular subscribers, tend to use the service for more leisurely or exploratory purposes, potentially spending more time per trip.

Conclusions¶

Most users are aged between their 20s and 40s, with a strong concentration of users born in the early 1990s. Older and younger age groups are underrepresented, suggesting the bike trip is most popular among younger adults.

Customers generally have longer and more varied trip durations, while subscribers tend to have shorter, more consistent trips. This suggests that subscribers may have regular trips.

Male subscribers take over most of the trips's, making the majority of trips, followed by female subscribers. Customers of all genders account for significantly fewer trips compared to subscribers.
